Hidden Valley Wilderness Retreat Market Analysis¶

The purpose of this project is to analyze the market for a Wilderness retreat. We want to define WHO is interested/interacts with the retreat, WHAT guests that have stayed like and do not like, and WHERE they are located. Using this information, the owners will be able to analyze what people do and don't like about the retreat, who their target market is and where they are located. Given this information, they can find ways to penetrate deeper into their current market or find ways to reach out to markets that they currently do not appeal to.¶

This data will also be used to develop a marketing strategy for a new stand alone tree house that will be opened in summer 2018.¶

1 Data Collection: First we need to collect data, for this project we will be collecting data off the facebook fan page¶

A script is ran to collect all the posts off of the fan page and stored into a csv. The Code is displayed below.¶

# https://github.com/minimaxir/facebook-page-post-scraper import urllib2 import json import datetime import csv import time #[1] First, install facebook-sdk (if this is not installed yet) #pip install facebook-sdk #[2] log into your Facebook account #[3] go to https://developers.facebook.com/tools/explorer #[4] copy your access token access_token = 'EAACEdEose0cBAHCnaa1ZBjh5Q05TX8wzeqJ8FzajoCOGXKS1Otnwa470T3JyLmcyW6bSrxYePoL2OTPgXdKwWwB0RDTB1U1jjxUVrKNrI7Pf41LsKhGyRsI1x0VPTv24tVx85E16E7MTjM2yZAXruPoStZBkghZCUIdNkbXJ4BhycD7x1auAVBbk1N7kqOgZD' page_id = "hiddenvalleywilderness" # a small fan page for demonstration purpose def request_until_succeed(url): req = urllib2.Request(url) success = False while success is False: try: response = urllib2.urlopen(req) if response.getcode() == 200: success = True except Exception, e: print e time.sleep(5) print "Error for URL %s: %s" % (url, datetime.datetime.now()) print "Retrying." return response.read() # Needed to write tricky unicode correctly to csv def unicode_normalize(text): return text.translate({ 0x2018:0x27, 0x2019:0x27, 0x201C:0x22, 0x201D:0x22, 0xa0:0x20 }).encode('utf-8') def getFacebookPageFeedData(page_id, access_token, num_statuses): # Construct the URL string; see http://stackoverflow.com/a/37239851 for # Reactions parameters base = "https://graph.facebook.com/v2.9" node = "/%s/posts" % page_id fields = "/?fields=message,link,created_time,type,name,id," + \ "comments.limit(0).summary(true),shares,reactions" + \ ".limit(0).summary(true)" parameters = "&limit=%s&access_token=%s" % (num_statuses, access_token) # you can change the duration of data collection #parameters = "/?fields=message,link,created_time,type,name,id,likes.limit(1).summary(true),comments.limit(1).summary(true),shares&since=2018-01-01&limit=%s&access_token=%s" % (num_statuses, access_token) # changed url = base + node + fields + parameters # retrieve data data = json.loads(request_until_succeed(url)) return data def getReactionsForStatus(status_id, access_token): # See http://stackoverflow.com/a/37239851 for Reactions parameters # Reactions are only accessable at a single-post endpoint base = "https://graph.facebook.com/v2.9" node = "/%s" % status_id reactions = "/?fields=" \ "reactions.type(LIKE).limit(0).summary(total_count).as(like)" \ ",reactions.type(LOVE).limit(0).summary(total_count).as(love)" \ ",reactions.type(WOW).limit(0).summary(total_count).as(wow)" \ ",reactions.type(HAHA).limit(0).summary(total_count).as(haha)" \ ",reactions.type(SAD).limit(0).summary(total_count).as(sad)" \ ",reactions.type(ANGRY).limit(0).summary(total_count).as(angry)" parameters = "&access_token=%s" % access_token url = base + node + reactions + parameters # retrieve data data = json.loads(request_until_succeed(url)) return data def processFacebookPageFeedStatus(status, access_token): # The status is now a Python dictionary, so for top-level items, # we can simply call the key. # Additionally, some items may not always exist, # so must check for existence first status_id = status['id'] status_message = '' if 'message' not in status.keys() else \ unicode_normalize(status['message']) link_name = '' if 'name' not in status.keys() else \ unicode_normalize(status['name']) status_type = status['type'] status_link = '' if 'link' not in status.keys() else \ unicode_normalize(status['link']) # Time needs special care since a) it's in UTC and # b) it's not easy to use in statistical programs. status_published = datetime.datetime.strptime( status['created_time'],'%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%S+0000') status_published = status_published + \ datetime.timedelta(hours=-5) # EST status_published = status_published.strftime( '%Y-%m-%d %H:%M:%S') # best time format for spreadsheet programs # Nested items require chaining dictionary keys. num_reactions = 0 if 'reactions' not in status else \ status['reactions']['summary']['total_count'] num_comments = 0 if 'comments' not in status else \ status['comments']['summary']['total_count'] num_shares = 0 if 'shares' not in status else status['shares']['count'] # Counts of each reaction separately; good for sentiment # Only check for reactions if past date of implementation: # http://newsroom.fb.com/news/2016/02/reactions-now-available-globally/ reactions = getReactionsForStatus(status_id, access_token) if \ status_published > '2016-02-24 00:00:00' else {} num_likes = 0 if 'like' not in reactions else \ reactions['like']['summary']['total_count'] # Special case: Set number of Likes to Number of reactions for pre-reaction # statuses num_likes = num_reactions if status_published < '2016-02-24 00:00:00' \ else num_likes def get_num_total_reactions(reaction_type, reactions): if reaction_type not in reactions: return 0 else: return reactions[reaction_type]['summary']['total_count'] num_loves = get_num_total_reactions('love', reactions) num_wows = get_num_total_reactions('wow', reactions) num_hahas = get_num_total_reactions('haha', reactions) num_sads = get_num_total_reactions('sad', reactions) num_angrys = get_num_total_reactions('angry', reactions) # Return a tuple of all processed data return (status_id, status_message, link_name, status_type, status_link, status_published, num_reactions, num_comments, num_shares, num_likes, num_loves, num_wows, num_hahas, num_sads, num_angrys) def scrapeFacebookPageFeedStatus(page_id, access_token): with open('%s_facebook_statuses.csv' % page_id, 'wb') as file: w = csv.writer(file) w.writerow(["status_id", "status_message", "link_name", "status_type", "status_link", "status_published", "num_reactions", "num_comments", "num_shares", "num_likes", "num_loves", "num_wows", "num_hahas", "num_sads", "num_angrys"]) has_next_page = True num_processed = 0 # keep a count on how many we've processed scrape_starttime = datetime.datetime.now() print "Scraping %s Facebook Page: %s\n" % (page_id, scrape_starttime) statuses = getFacebookPageFeedData(page_id, access_token, 100) while has_next_page: for status in statuses['data']: # Ensure it is a status with the expected metadata if 'reactions' in status: w.writerow(processFacebookPageFeedStatus(status, access_token)) # output progress occasionally to make sure code is not # stalling num_processed += 1 if num_processed % 100 == 0: print "%s Statuses Processed: %s" % \ (num_processed, datetime.datetime.now()) # if there is no next page, we're done. if 'paging' in statuses.keys() and 'next' in statuses['paging'] and statuses['paging']['next']: statuses = json.loads(request_until_succeed( statuses['paging']['next'])) else: has_next_page = False print "\nDone!\n%s Statuses Processed in %s" % \ (num_processed, datetime.datetime.now() - scrape_starttime) if __name__ == '__main__': scrapeFacebookPageFeedStatus(page_id, access_token)

This Script, when run in the command line results in a csv file being created that contains all the information about the facebook posts. Collected facebook posts equals 63 posts.¶

In [537]:
# Remove useless numbers and alphanumerical words
documents = [re.sub("[^a-zA-Z]+", " ", str(text)) for text in Post_texts]

# tokenize
texts = [[word for word in text.lower().split() ] for text in documents]

# stemming words: having --> have; friends --> friend
lmtzr = WordNetLemmatizer()
texts = [[lmtzr.lemmatize(word) for word in text ] for text in texts]

#porter_stemmer = PorterStemmer()

#texts = [[porter_stemmer.stem(word) for word in text ] for text in texts]

# remove common words 
stoplist = stopwords.words('english')
texts = [[word for word in text if word not in stoplist] for text in texts]

#remove short words
texts = [[ word for word in tokens if len(word) >= 3 ] for tokens in texts]
extra_stopwords = ['n','u','nthe','com','www','even','could','two','may', 'llc','best','http']
extra_stoplist = extra_stopwords
texts = [[word for word in text if word not in extra_stoplist] for text in texts]

tokens = tokens.lower()

tokens2 = word_tokenize(tokens)
for token in tokens2:
    if token != "u":
        post_tokens.append(token)
fdist = nltk.FreqDist(post_tokens)

fdist.plot(25)

The Graph above displays the most common words used in posts by the facebook page itself. As you can see from the most common used words, the page looks to highlight the treehouses, nature, airbnb (where they are rented out), and the beauty of the business. Other topics talk about the wilderness, hiking, ponds. We will use this data later to see if their posts are accurately tailored to what their customers are looking for.¶

r = csv.reader(open('hiddenvalleywilderness_facebook_statuses.csv', 'rb'))

    if (first == False):
        Total_Posts += 1
        if (int(row[6]) > 0):
            Total_PostsWLikes += 1
            Total_Likes += int(row[6])
            
        if (int(row[7]) > 0):
            Comments += 1
            Total_Comments += int(row[7])

Information gathered by these analytics give us some key insight into the popularity of the page.¶

1. The page is big enough that most of it's posts have received at least one like¶

2.It averages 11 likes per post¶

3. it has a popularity ratinig of 18.37 which is fairly good.¶

4. Only about 20% of posts have comments on them¶

5. The posts have averaged about 1 comment per post¶

6. Their commitment score is a 1.61. This shows us that they don't have a lot of followers that actually interact with their posts. This gives us insight into why people follow this page. Many of them follow the page most likely to see the content they post, but aren't dedicated enough to actually get involved with the posts.¶

9. All the posts have at least one share.¶

10. The pages posts average 2.31 shares per post¶

11. They do have posts that gain popularity¶

def getCommentMessages(d):
    comm_list=[]  # Empty list to hold comments messages.
    if isinstance(d, dict):  # Check to see that a dictionary was passed into the function
        if isinstance(d['data'][0], dict):  # Are there actual comments data nodes?
            for i in d['data']:   # Iterate through the nodes under the ['comments']['data]
                if i['message']:  # Check that value exists
                    if isinstance(i, dict):  
                        #print i['message'], i['like_count']
                        comm_list.append([i['message'],i['like_count']])  # Append message to comments list
            return comm_list  # Return the comments list

def getReviewMessages(d):
    review_list=[]  # Empty list to hold comments messages.
    if isinstance(d, dict):  # Check to see that a dictionary was passed into the function
        if isinstance(d['data'][0], dict):  # Are there actual comments data nodes?
            for i in d['data']:   # Iterate through the nodes under the ['comments']['data]
                if i['review_text']:  # Check that value exists
                    if isinstance(i, dict):  
                        #print i['message'], i['like_count']
                        review_list.append([i['review_text'],i['rating']])  # Append message to comments list
                        
            return review_list  # Return the comments list

# stemming words: having --> have; friends --> friend

extra_stopwords = ['n','u','nthe','com','www','even','could','two','may', 'llc','best','http']

texts3 = [[word for word in text if word not in extra_stoplist] for text in texts3]

Sentiment Analysis¶

Evaluate whether the reviews are positive or negative. We know that Hidden Valley Wilderness Retreat has a perfect 5/5 rating on Airbnb and Facebook. However we want to evaluate whether these ratings are accurate. Considering that Airbnb has a mutual rating system, it is possible for ratings to be skewed since people may rate something positive in the hopes that the favor will be returned¶

In [392]:
from pattern.en import sentiment
import csv
import pandas as pd

import re

import nltk
from nltk.corpus import stopwords
In [403]:
positive_review = []
negative_review = []
neutral_review = []
Review_Scores = []
for row in combinedReviews:
    score = sentiment(row)
    if score[0] > 0:
        positive_review.append(row)
    elif score[0] == 0:
        neutral_review.append(row)
    else:
        negative_review.append(row)
    Review_Scores.append({score, row})

Business Data and Understanding Topic Modeling Results¶

The results of the topic modeling gives us some insight into hidden topics in customer reviews left for Hidden Valley Wilderness Retreat¶

-Getaways: One of the biggest hidden topics was getaways. A lot of the reviews talk about how they came to hidden valley wilderness retreat as an anniversery, weekend getaway, or retreat. Those reviews mention the peacefulness of the property, the trails, screened in porch, and the candles.¶

- Evening: This topic highlights the beauty of the evenings in the valey. They talk about their trips giving them time to think, observe nature, walk trails surrounded by ponds, and eat good food.¶

- Time: This topic was prevelant in quite a few reviews. Talking about how they wish they had more time to get away. This topic also mentions the drive and distance to the retreat.¶

- Local: A lot of reviews mention local things in the area such as downtown leavenworth. Going downtown and eat and shop.¶

- Peacefulness: The most prevelent terms that showed up in the topics relate to the peacefulness of the retreat. Mentions of the quietness, animals, relaxing, walks, enjoyment, wonderful show up in all the topics.¶

- Treehouse: This one is not surprising but a big topic deals with the tree houses the retreat has to offer.¶

The purpose of this project was to gain insight into the market that stays at hidden valley wilderness retreat. This is important information because the retreat is opening up a new stand alone tree house and this information will give them insight into how and who to market their pruduct too. The word clouds created also serve as excellent marketing material if they so choose.¶

Based on analysis the most common thing said in the reviews is that they wanted to come back. Using this insight, the first people that should be targeted with advertising are people that have previously stayed at the retreat. These people can be targeted and informed of the new tree house opening soon which would give them a reason to return to the retreat while also getting a new and improved experience.¶

Based on analysis of the posts on Facebook from the company fan page, The posts are mainly informative. They talk about information about the retreat, such as location and ammenities. When you compare this to the comments and the reviews you see a contrast. The reviews and comments focus on the retreat being a place to have anniverseries, weekend getaways, and peaceful relaxing. I conclude that advertising for the page should have an increase focus on the experience and reasons people come to the retreat to stay.¶

Additional information attained from the reviews points me to conclude that a large portion of the guests are not necessarily local. Many of the reviews talk about having a getaway from the city and going somewhere quiet and peaceful. This is very important information because it allows hidden valley wilderness retreat to target demographics in the city and focus less on local. They should be targeting people in Kansas City as well as downtown leavenworth. This insight also presents a possible untapped market in the local area. Much of the nearby population lives on a military base (Fort Leavenworth). I conclude that based on the information about the retreat being a great place for a getaway, anniverseries, birthdays etc, Hidden Valley wilderness retreat should attempt to penetrate this market. They could do this by advertising themselves as a place where military couples could get away to somewhere peaceful and celebrate a birthday, anniversary, or just a romantic weekend.¶
